Torrential rain across northern India has killed at least 22 people, as well as causing landslides and flash floods in the region, authorities and local media said on Monday.

Schools in New Delhi were closed after heavy rains lashed the national capital over the weekend, and authorities in the Himalayan states of Himachal Pradesh and Uttarakhand asked people not to venture out of their homes unless necessary.

At least 22 people died in floods and landslides in the northern states of Himachal Pradesh, Uttarakhand, Uttar Pradesh, Jammu and Kashmir and Punjab on Sunday, the Times of India newspaper reported.

In the northern state of Himachal Pradesh, flash floods over the weekend brought down a bridge and swept away several hutments. Authorities used helicopters to rescue people stranded on roads and bridges because of the rain, footage from Reuters partner ANI showed.

Panchvaktra Temple Submerged In Water Due To Spate In Beas River | Himachal Pradesh Rain

Panchvaktra Temple, Mandi
Situated at the confluence of the Rivers Suketi and Beas, the serene beauty of the Panchvaktra temple attracts a large number of visitors from across the country. The temple stands on a huge platform and is very well furnished. Panchvaktra temple is a supreme shrine dedicated to Lord Shiv. The temple is built in the typical Shikhara architecture style which looks astounding. Temple got its name from the five faced statue image of Lord Shiva, out of which only three can be seen when viewed from the front.
It is one of the protected monuments which comes under the Archaeological Survey of India and has been declared a national site. Inside the Panchvaktra temple, there is a huge statue of Lord Shiv. The statue has five faces which depict about the different character of Lord Shiv- Aghora, Ishana, Tat Purusha, Vaamdeva and Rudra. Angora is the destructive nature, Ishana is omnipresent and omnipotent, Tat Purusha is his ego, Vaamdeva is the female facet and Rudra is his creative and destructive aspect. Panchvaktra is defined as the union of all these.
The foundation date of the Panhvaktra temple is still unknown. As per the historical facts, the temple was restored under the reign of Sidh Sen's kingship (1684-1727) as it was damaged due to flood. Main porch or Mandap of the temple is supported by 4 minutely carved pillars.
It's a peaceful place; tranquillity descends in the aroma of the temple. A silent meditation here can bestow the people with good mental health and purify their souls. Panchvaktra temple, no doubt, is our prestigious heritage.

â€¢

It is sometimes easy to forget that we have no control out here over any natural forces. As I write this, many cities in North India have been struck with a flood and more than 40 deaths have been recorded.
Delhi has been inundated with 153mm of rain, the highest precipitation in a single day in July in 40 years and Himachal Pradesh received a monthâ€™s rainfall in a day at the weekend. Delhi, Punjab, and Himachal Pradesh have received 112%, 100% and 70% more rainfall than average so far. Rain is hard to forecast and varies considerably, but scientists say climate change is making the monsoon stronger and more erratic. 

I canâ€™t help but think sometimes that the apparent ease of modern life is an illusion, and those who believe the illusion real live in it only in very temporary ways. I canâ€™t help but think of the human obsession to have control over the uncontrollable. 

I looked at myself in the mirror this morning as I splashed my face with water and I thought about India, the rivers, the wells, the dams, the drains, the pumps, the assigned hours for running tap water, water canisters in big trucks and I thought about the affluence of owning water, bottling it and selling it. I thought about the might of modern industrialism, the way weâ€™ve desperately turned everything into a canvas for our projected dreams of capital and the dangerous desire to use all resources until we cannot.

I thought about it all and came up with nothing that made sense. Beyond everything, a certain external reality remains, resisting interpretation. There is nothing anomalous about calamity. People die, the race goes on, the supply chain never stops, the pursuit for control continues, the illusion persists.

Torrential rain across northern India has killed at least 22 people, as well as causing landslides and flash floods in the region, authorities and local media said on Monday.

Schools in New Delhi were closed after heavy rains lashed the national capital over the weekend, and authorities in the Himalayan states of Himachal Pradesh and Uttarakhand asked people not to venture out of their homes unless necessary.

At least 22 people died in floods and landslides in the northern states of Himachal Pradesh, Uttarakhand, Uttar Pradesh, Jammu and Kashmir and Punjab on Sunday, the Times of India newspaper reported.

In the northern state of Himachal Pradesh, flash floods over the weekend brought down a bridge and swept away several hutments.

Subject: Climate Change and Corruption!

These days we watch the news in horror as heavy rains and the resultant flooding particularly in North are wiping away homes, businesses and killing people!  All of this is now becoming a regular feature not only India but also in many parts of the world !

Itâ€™s quite evident that Climate Change is causing of all these disasters and the Indian ruling Politicians will show concern and also offer some sort of assistance/relief ( which can never be enough!) to the affected people! 

The Fact however is these disasters  are forecasted only to get worse and I do not see the Indian Government working at the same pace to mitigate the threat !  Specific corporates backing the ruling party as allowed to bypass critical Environmental guidelines to exponentially grow their fossil fuel business and also high level of corruption is allowing all sort of illegalities Ie Hill Cutting, Sand Mining, Filling of low lying areas/water bodies, chopping thousands of trees, destroying/poisoning mangroves etc. The latter is happening all over India and one does not need to Go Far; just watch whatâ€™s happening now in Goa ! 

The fact in India is that Indians/Goans (at least appear) to be very religious and when tragedy strikes, itâ€™s without saying that prayers/pleas to the respective Godâ€™s will exponentially increase !  But should â€œGod really help those who canâ€™t help themselvesâ€. We have in our power to stand up/confront against corrupt politicians in Goa for instance( Govt, Panchayats, Municipalities etc) and even specific/destructive  real estate entities;  but how many of us do ? Most of us are happy with Politicians for their propaganda/divisive speeches or freebees/money /business contracts/jobs etc and refuse to speak up either in speech, action or via the ballot box!

It pains me to say this but God Forbid; should such disasters strike closer to home, Goans generally will deserve it !

We all know a good sunset is beautiful, but have you ever thought about the science behind why sunsets are so colorful? Those iconic pink and orange colors you often see at sunset are the result of a phenomenon known as scattering. Essentially, light rays coming from the sky hit small molecules and particles in the air, causing them to change directions and, well, scatter! Knowing this means we are able to predict a good sunset!

Four people died and seven others were injured in Uttarkashi, Uttarakhand, when big rocks fell from the hills due to heavy rain. The rocks landed on three vehicles carrying a group of people who were returning to Madhya Pradesh after visiting Gangotri. The incident happened late in the evening and there were around 30 people in the vehicles.
